People living and registered with a GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and to apply for potential participation in testing.
The programme comes with taxpayers £10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute the drugs after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to collect clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and large-scale implementation.
Simon Stevens added: This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in over 30 years of efforts to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust, said: "We are witnessing a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if given correctly and to patients at risk, will offer the possibility of a change in the English HIV epidemic.
From September, the NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and does not require a partner to be persuaded, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
