"I've been looking for consistency and objectivity", said Errett, owner of the San Francisco-based e-commerce company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
So she asked for help from the outside.
New HR startups are constantly emerging in the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By developing and licensing software with a specific purpose of measuring employee obligations, startups enable companies to conduct rapid voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass their superiors and contact direct managers.
"There are tools on the market like Food and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that in three years, she gained greater awareness of what her employees think and feel because of Glint.
In addition to quick surveys and team-specific voting, Glint offers a company temperature map and a general overview of the highest-complaint groups as well as a low-rating manager overview - allowing users to work on correction.
Companies are starting to realize the need to look at the workplace culture - in case they become another Uber - which is getting into scandal after a former employee posted a blog post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let's Talk Payments, a technical and financial development website, the global control, regulation and compliance industry could be worth over $118.8 billion by 2020.
A Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandal.
Convercent's nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently took over the business.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customizable flash surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
"The Court of Public Opinion has authorised regulators", said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent.
If a company is convicted of mistreatment of its employees or unethical behaviour - and if regulators do not intervene - it can face costly consequences from a customer boycott, employee exhaustion or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employee awareness of company policies and procedures and ensure an easy way to contact corporate management.
In the past, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to check the company's phone number or email address, file a formal complaint, and hope for a successful solution.
Often, this was a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Deputy Director General Ruby Tuesday, who said that there was no reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now that the company uses Convercent, it's ensuring rapid detection and resolution of problems that never before have been reached by managers sitting in offices miles away from a real resolution of complaints - for example, discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
It is close to a holistic, overall view of employee experience, said Vitrano, who heads Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
We also protect shareholders from employee litigation.
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed following Enron's failure to abide by employee ethics, Quinlan said.
But it wasn't until social media shed light on the whole thing that companies began to realize that in the online world, they couldn't just hide their skeletons in a closet.
"Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith", Quinlan added.
Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It's a business model and an opportunity that's being embraced by the bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
Convercent, as part of its February campaign, pulled out a total of $10 million from companies like Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital and ultimately withdrew $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners and raised $60 million over the course of the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
The growing number of studies clearly confirms that today's workers expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are not the main advantages.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and to dedicate their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
"When people are happy at work, they feel their voices are heard and their work is rewarding, they strive for the success of the company", said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses Convercent and Glint.
Investors make a profit when companies succeed and companies thrive when employees are happy.
And when an analytical tool comes on the market to ensure employee engagement and commitment to the company, it's no wonder that there are a lot of investors to support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, there can be big changes.
And if change doesn't happen quickly - at worst - it can cause disappointment and disinterest in employees.
"Once you ask for 4,000 opinions, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations", said Russell Raath, consulting director at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies rely too heavily on data alone.
Because once you don't get things done, the employees start asking themselves, "Did they even hear me?"
They care about me?
And if not, why should I care?' "
Madison Reed, which now conducts a monthly staff survey, thanks to Glinth, can solve the problem in one day, Errett said.
After gathering feedback from employees who were frustrated with the slow decision-making and quality of communication, Errett managed to reorganize several teams within the company and begin communication training to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important perspective on its employees and hopes to achieve high long-term employment in an industry known for its frequent layoffs.
If you do not strive to create a transparent work environment, employees will not trust you, added Vitrano.
And once you start losing employees, you're going to lose customers.
And with the influx of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt.
