Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may alleviate the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
Red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare for your digestive system.
However, a new study suggests the opposite: A diet high in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
An incurable disease that affects up to 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 patients in the United Kingdom, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually advised not to eat meat or dairy products to alleviate symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington found that the essential amino acid tryptophan found in the protein helps to build immune cells that support the gut's resistance.
Dr. Marco Colonna, who led the study, explained that immune cells protect the gut and help to remove harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
Once the scales tilt to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
In the study, the scientists found the presence of immune cells that promote the body's tolerance of specific bacteria in the stomach of mice.
To make cells, this bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins.
Professor Colonna said: "We found a link between a type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - that is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body's tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells had.
He also suggested that if the same thing were to be found in humans, a combination of L. reuteri bacteria and tryptophan-rich foods would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
In a study of a certain type of immune cell that promotes body tolerance, postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas found that one group of test mice had these cells, while another group of the same mice raised separately lacked cells.
She concluded that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The gut of mice was tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked the gut microbiome - so they didn't develop this type of immune cell - were given L. reuteri bacteria - and they developed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred small amounts of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
The immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removal of the active ingredient from the liquid, it was shown to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-octane acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent, and when the tryptophan doses were halved, the number of cells was halved.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the tryptophan by-products of L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: "We should all probably strive to develop these cells, because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri bacteria may increase the cell population.
