President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials were watching a product show from all 50 states.
A Connecticut helicopter was built next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a forklifts from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the helicopter's presence less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn as part of an emergency, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for the helicopter's management.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event", Commander HMX-1 wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy chief of air operations, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the show, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and remain in place until the entire area was fully cleared as planned between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The email also said that if there was a delay in the departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to the working hours regulations.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening, along with the helicopter and a security unit.
From the records - obtained by TIME - it was not clear whether the second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government assets for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible infringements of this Regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was fine", the commander wrote.
"It sounds like you're being blocked", the deputy commander wrote.
This "Made in America" show was designated by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political underpinnings.
During his time at the event, the president advocated for health care reform, which was passed by the Senate, and spoke of trying to keep the government order in place.
The use of air transport vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
The president uses them for travel.
But their presence, purely for presentation reasons, is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane flew in the background at his first-ever campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida.
"The White House is pleased to see the 'Made in America' showcase products from all 50 states that make Americans from American materials", said press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and South Lawn and practice possible approaches with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 drill landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the current crew training, a state official said.
The helicopter unit took off on the same day as part of the non-presidential support missions for another 11 hours.
The White House said no further props were paid from taxpayer money.
Sikorsky's spokesman said the company was not in any way involved in the negotiations to deploy the helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights and the exact costs related to the overview are difficult to determine according to the Navy's statement.
